Himalayan Climbing Expeditions

Ekaterina Cheliadinova

01/11/2020

La base de donnes Himalayan Climbing Expeditions permet dobserver toutes les expditions dans lHimalaya au Npal. La base de donnes sappuie sur les archives de lexpdition dElizabeth Hawley, journaliste de longue date base Katmandou, et est complte par des informations recueillies partir de livres, de revues alpines et de correspondance avec des alpinistes himalayens.

Les donnes couvrent toutes les expditions de 1905 au printemps 2019 jusqu plus de 465 sommets importants au Npal. Des expditions des deux cts des sommets frontaliers tels que lEverest, Cho Oyu, Makalu et Kangchenjunga ainsi que vers certains sommets frontaliers plus petits sont galement incluses. Les donnes sur les expditions vers les sommets de trekking sont incluses pour les premires tentatives, les premires ascensions et les accidents majeurs.

2. ombien de femmes et dhommes ont particip aux expditions chaque anne?

members %>% 
  filter(year>y) %>% 
  group_by(year, sex) %>% 
  summarise(n = n()) %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = sex,values_from = n) %>% 
  mutate(perc = F/(F+M)) ->df


members %>% 
  filter(year>y) %>% 
  group_by(year, sex) %>% 
  summarise(n = n()) %>% 
  drop_na(sex) %>% 
  ggplot( aes(year, n , fill = sex)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", width = 1, color = 'black',position = position_stack(reverse = TRUE)) +
  labs(y = "count",
       x = "year",
       title = "Le nombre de femmes et d'hommes chaque anne")

3. Est-ce que chaque anne en moyenne le nombre de femmes participant aux expditions a augment?
members %>% 
  filter(year>1970) %>% 
  group_by(year, sex) %>% 
  summarise(n = n()) %>% 
  drop_na(sex) %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from =sex, values_from = n) %>%
  mutate(F = replace_na(F,0)) %>% 
  mutate(taux = F/(M+F)) %>% 
  ggplot( aes(year, taux)) +
  geom_line()+
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE)

4. Quelles sont les principales raisons pour lesquelles les expditions ont chou avant et aprs 1980?
expeditions %>% 
  filter(year <1980 & termination_reason != 'Success (main peak)' & termination_reason != 'Success (subpeak)' &  termination_reason != 'Success (claimed)') %>% 
  drop_na(termination_reason) %>% 
  group_by(termination_reason) %>% 
  summarise(n = n()) %>% 
  arrange(-n) %>% 
  top_n(5) %>% 
  kbl(col.names = c('termination reason','count')) %>% 
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover", "condensed"))

6. Quels sont les pics les plus dangereux parmi les plus populaires?
expeditions %>% 
  group_by(peak_name) %>% 
  summarise(sum = sum(member_deaths)+sum(hired_staff_deaths), n = sum(members)+sum(hired_staff)) %>% 
  mutate(taux = 100*sum/n) %>% 
  arrange(-taux) %>% 
  left_join(select(peaks,peak_name,height_metres)) %>% 
  filter(n>1000) %>% 
  slice(1:10) %>% 
  mutate(taux = round(taux, 3)) %>% 
  kbl(col.names = c('pick','nombre de morts','nombre total','taux de mortalite','hauteur')) %>% 
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover", "condensed")) %>% 
  row_spec(row = 7,color = 'red')

7. Quelle saison est la plus approprie pour une expdition c.--d.avec le taux de russite le plus lev?
expeditions$success <- with(expeditions,ifelse(termination_reason == 'Success (main peak)' | termination_reason == 'Success (subpeak)' |  termination_reason == 'Success (claimed)', TRUE,FALSE))

expeditions %>% 
  group_by(season, success) %>% 
  summarise(n_success = n()) %>% 
  filter(season!='Unknown') %>% 
  group_by(season) %>% 
  mutate(Percentage = n_success/sum(n_success), total = sum(n_success)) %>% 
  filter(success == TRUE) %>% 
  arrange(-Percentage) %>% 
  select(season,Percentage) %>% 
  kbl(col.names = c('Saison','taux de russite')) %>% 
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover", "condensed"))

12. Quels pays ont connu le plus de succs depuis 1985?
expeditions$suc <- with(expeditions,ifelse(termination_reason == 'Success (main peak)' | termination_reason == 'Success (subpeak)' |  termination_reason == 'Success (claimed)', 1,0))

expeditions %>%
  filter(year>1985) %>%
  left_join(members,by = 'expedition_id') %>% 
  group_by(expedition_id, citizenship,suc ) %>% 
  summarise(n = n()) ->d

d[d$expedition_id %in% names(which(table(d$expedition_id) < 2)), ] %>% 
  group_by(citizenship,suc) %>% 
  summarise(n = n()) %>% 
  group_by(citizenship) %>% 
  mutate(Percentage = 100*n/sum(n), total = sum(n)) %>% 
  filter(suc==1&total>=50) %>%
  drop_na() %>% 
  arrange(-Percentage) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(y = reorder(citizenship,Percentage),x = Percentage))+
  geom_col( fill='#FF6666')+
  labs(y = "pays",
       x = "taux de russite")+
  annotate("text", x = 36, y = 4, label = 31.97, color = 'black')

13. Quelle est la meilleure compagnie dexpdition?
expeditions %>% 
  group_by(trekking_agency, suc) %>% 
  summarise(n = n()) %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from =suc, values_from = n) %>% 
  rename(fail = '0') %>%
  rename(success = '1') %>%
  mutate(fail = replace_na(fail,0),success = replace_na(success,0),total = success+fail, percent_of_success = success/total) %>% 
  filter(total>=100) %>% 
  arrange(-percent_of_success) %>% 
  drop_na() %>% 
  head(5) %>% 
  kbl(col.names = c('trekking agency','success','fail','total','percent of success')) %>% 
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover", "condensed"))
